<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910111-0072</DOCNO><DOCID>910111-0072.</DOCID><HL>   U.S. Jury Indicts   Peoples Heritage   Officers, Borrowers   ----   By Paulette Thomas   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>01/11/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- A grand jury indicted 10 executives andborrowers at failed Peoples Heritage Federal Savings andamp; LoanAssociation of Salina, Kan., charging that they defrauded thethrift of more than $105 million.   In one of the largest federal thrift indictments ever, thegroup, including former chairman Thomas D. Dunn Jr.,president James Cruce and chief lending officer ThomasBurger, was charged with 32 counts of bank fraud, conspiracyand making false statements. The charges stem from allegedsham loan transactions and stock schemes.</LP><TEXT>   The case is on the Justice Department's list of 100highest-priority cases of thrift fraud, a spokesman said.Peoples Heritage was seized by the government in August 1989,and its branches were sold piecemeal in January 1990. Half ofits deposits came from out-of-state deposit brokers, whosought failing thrifts that were paying high interest ratesto attract deposits, a practice that has helped boost thecost of the Sandamp;L cleanup. The failure of Peoples Heritage willcost taxpayers as much as $900 million.   According to one indictment, the three executives andseveral borrowers used $70 million in Peoples Heritage loansto form limited partnerships to purchase real estate andother assets.   A separate indictment charged that the three PeoplesHeritage executives approved more than $35 million in loansto borrowers to purchase Texas real estate and AmeriwestFinancial Corp. stock held by the three executives. Ameriwestis now known as ABQ Savings Bank, in Albuquerque, N.M. Theexecutives didn't disclose to other board members that theborrowers would use the Peoples Heritage funds to acquiretheir holdings, according to the indictments.   James Eisenbrandt, an attorney for Mr. Dunn, the formerchairman, said he hadn't yet reviewed the indictment andcouldn't comment. Messrs. Cruce and Burger couldn't bereached for comment.</TEXT></DOC>